issue.title: Remove Peripheral/PeripheralRef
issue.body:
### Submission Checklist üìù - [x] I have updated existing examples or added new ones (if applicable). - [x] I have used `cargo fmt` command to ensure that all changed code is formatted correctly. - [x] I have used `cargo clippy` command to ensure that all changed code passes latest Clippy nightly lints. - [x] My changes were added to the [`CHANGELOG.md`](https://github.com/esp-rs/esp-idf-hal/blob/main/esp-idf-hal/CHANGELOG.md) in the **_proper_** section. ### Pull Request Details üìñ This PR removes the `Peripheral` trait and the `PeripheralRef` struct which turned out to be [unsound](https://github.com/embassy-rs/embassy/issues/3997). Those are replaced with a simpler pattern, where the peripheral can still be reborrowed, however that now happens by using an explicit `periph::reborrow()` method, rather than just using `&mut periph`. On the other hand, the signatures of the driver-constructor functions are now much simpler. E.g., where a driver used to take a pin peripheral, the signature used to be: - `fn new(pin: impl Peripheral

+ 'd)` ... which is now just: - `fn new(pin: impl InputPin + 'd)` The flip side of the coin is that all peripherals are now generic by a lifetime, i.e. `Gpio1` is now `Gpio1<'d>`. Peripherals passed by moving are e.g. `Gpio1<'static>` though. Only `gpio1.reborrow()` would end up with a non-static lifetime on the returned reborrowed pin1. Note that `reborrow` is unsafe specifically in `esp-idf-*` and unlike all other baremetal HAL crates. The justification for that is that `esp-idf-*` wraps existing C drivers, and unsure whether `core::mem::forget`-ing a driver (and thus its C twin), and then re-using its peripherals (which were reborrowed in the original driver and thus available again once the original driver instance is forgotten) in a new driver instance of the same or different driver type is actually OK, while the original driver instance - albeit forgotten - is actually active. The forgotten driver can be active, because most drivers install a custom ISR handler which will not be removed when the driver is forgotten and the ISR would still be called and so on. While this might not be a problem per-se, if another driver installs an ISR for the same peripheral, that might or might not be a problem. Until we check the behavior of every driver, we just don't know, hence why (initially) `reborrow` is unsafe. Note that this problem is not new - the same problem existed with `Peripheral` / `PeripheralRef` but I was impossible to mark the `&mut periph` as an unsafe operation at that time. #### Description Unlike e.g. `embassy-nrf` which currently requires an extra wrapper around the peripheral when passing to drivers - `Peri`, `esp-idf-hal` utilizes the same pattern as `esp-hal` - passing the peripheral directly. In order no to end up with driver signatures where the peripheral lifetime is repeated twice (though the inconvenience of this is a bit questionable?), e.g. `PinDriver<'d, Gpio0<'d>, Input>`, the PR removes the peripheral generic from `PinDriver`. In other words, `PinDriver` is now simply `PinDriver<'d, Input>`, where the incurred cost is that the driver has an extra `u8` field which represents the pin number (i.e. the driver is no longer a ZST). While this might look like a significant overhead, note that all other drivers were never ZST types anyway, and only `PinDriver` was. There are two drivers where - for type safety - having some generification of the driver cannot be avoided. Namely: - `AdcChannelDriver` needs to be generified by its ADC unit peripheral (we actually even generify it by its channel so that we can still preserve compat with e-hal 0.2), or else the the user might pass a channel (pin) from ADC2 for oneshot measurement with an `AdcDriver` instantiated for ADC1 - LEDC on the esp32 supports high-speed channels, but these only work with the high speed timers, so we have to ensure, that high speed channels are always used with high speed timers The above cases required generification of the relevant drivers by their peripherals and hence the double-lifetime. This is now work-arounded by having those types generified by an **associated type** (with a `'static` lifetime) that each such peripheral has. I.e. where `AdcDriver` used to be `AdcDriver<'d, ADC1>` - which would've resulted in `AdcDriver<'d, ADC1<'d>>` with the removal of `Peripheral`, it is now `AdcDriver<'d, ADCU<0>>`. Again, whether this is a win net-net is questionable to me, but this is not significantly worse either. Note also that with the loss of its peripheral generic, `PinDriver` also lost all its `into_` methods, because the capabilities of the wrapped pin peripheral are no longer preserved in the driver. No big deal I think, because the `PinDriver` was the only one still keeping `into_` methods anyway. The equivalent of doing it without `into_` methods is to use the `periph.reborrow` pattern. Finally, `Periph::new()` is now renamed to `Periph::steal()` (and there is an `Any??Pin::steal(pin_id)`) to unify the terminology across `esp-idf-hal` and the other HALs. #### Testing To be tested by running the examples.

comment.body:
> > > I think this goes into right direction.
> > > One question that i don't seam to see how its handeld currently, if i want to transition from state A to B, how we should do that without going through a drop/disable state?
> > > Currently we can for exampel do this
> > > ```
> > >     let pin_driver = PinDriver::input(per.pins.gpio0)?;
> > >     let pin_driver_output = pin_driver.into_output()?;
> > > ```
> > 
> > 
> > `into_` are no longer there. This is actually covered in the PR description, also as to why.
> 
> ah yeah i missed that part.
> 
> Still i dont think the equivalent would be to use reborrow in a into scenario if i understand it correctly. Please correct me if i am wrong, but the idea of into was to "reconfigure" the driver without droping it. Because if i drop it we run the drop handler and that is potentially an unwanted glitch on the gpio line since it is than going into disabled state.
> 
> So if i previously just go from PinDriver A mode into PinDriver B mode that would not happen now. How can a user still does a transition without introducing glitches on the gpio lines?

You might have a point here. I had forgotten that `into_` were _also_ used as a workaround for changing the mode of the pin without dropping (and thus resetting) it.

The problem is that if we want to preserve the `into_` methods, we need to preserve/restore the `T` type of the pin into the `PinDriver` (or else we don't know what are the capabilities of the pin and therefore we don't know which `into_` methods we should support) and this is totally absolutely NOK because - with the introduction of lifetimes on the `GpioXX<'a>` peripheral, the signature of `PinDriver` would become `PinDriver<'a, GpioXX<'a>, Input>`, i.e. the double-repetition of `'a` which this PR went at great length to avoid in the few remaining drivers (ADC) that need to preserve the peripheral type. That's why the `ADCU1` / `ADCU2` structures as well as all `ADCCHXX` structures were introduced in the first place. :(

So I'm strongly on the opinion that we should say "bye bye" to the `into_` methods and workaround the drop glitch in some other way.

What is `esp-hal` doing on drop? Keeping the last configured state of the pin? As we know if they DO so, this is not ideal, because this is against all other drivers and against what the other "embassy" "modern" HALs do.

But if I have to choose between preserving the `T` type and doing the `esp-hal` cheat of "I'll do nothing on drop" I would perhaps say the latter is the lesser evdeil. :(

Another idea: we could also have an `unsafe` or "unchecked" variant of `into_` where you can `into_output` a pin which is not really an output pin. That might still be better than keeping the `T` type around.

performed_via_github_app.description:
Publish incredibly high performance websites and applications right from GitHub. The Netlify platform connects your repositories to an all-in-one workflow for global CDN deployment, continuous integration, and automatic (and free) HTTPS. Each time you commit changes, Netlify builds your site, prerenders markup, and optimizes assets on dedicated build infrastructure. Easily create an entirely automated workflows for your web applications

## Features

### Push your site live, directly from GitHub
Deploy your site to an ultra-redundant global CDN that‚Äôs purpose built for serving pages and assets quickly and consistently.

### Automate deployment
Netlify‚Äôs built-in Continuous Deployment automatically runs your build commands and deploys the result whenever you push to your Git repository.

### Add a custom domain
Purchase domains and manage DNS zones and records right inside of Netlify.

### HTTPS is automatic
Your site will automatically be secured with a free TLS certificate from Let‚Äôs Encrypt.

### Deploy Previews
Netlify‚Äôs Deploy Previews streamlined your workflow by giving you a unique, permanent URL to check what your changes will be like in production whenever you submit a pull request.

### And a lot more!
Netlify includes solutions for forms, identity, and even custom functions powered by AWS Lambda. And all this functionality can be configured directly in your repo.

This GitHub Action is not targeting the book source documentation. It is mainly checking whether the Quarto notebook can render properly and ensuring that no PR or other changes break the notebook rendering. The book source documentation is not related to this PR.
If you think it would be useful, we could consider showing the rendered outputs in the documentation, but I am not sure whether that is needed. In the book source, I was thinking of adding documentation to let users  know that they can run the PEcAn workflow using the notebook that is currently included.
